<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-106-324 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 985 149</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  July 15 1991 v8 n28 p13(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Texaco has difficulty finding ISDN a home: central technologydepartment identifies ISDN's potential. (Integrated ServicesDigital Network)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wallace, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Texaco Inc has researched all facets of Integrated ServicesDigital Network (ISDN) technology and delineated the assets andliabilities of the service for business units but has found fewuses for it.andP;  Texaco uses ISDN to support a printer-sharingapplication at its Houston headquarters.andP;  Problems preventingwider use include the high-cost of long-haul services and lack ofterminal portability.andP;  The company's Information TechnologyDepartment (ITD) wrote a paper for internal distribution andconducted technology conferences.andP;  The paper defined ISDN,delineated the current state of ISDN standards, reported thesignificance of Common Channel Signaling System 7 (CCS7) andexplained carrier and switch vendor implementations of ISDN.andO;Texaco loaded the paper into its Technology Information ExchangeSystem (TIES) and staged a multivendor demonstration at atechnology conference in the fall of 1990.andP;  Attendees wereimpressed but demand has not increased significantly; high cost isa major deterrent.andP;  ITD officials remain committed to thetechnology.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Texaco Inc. (Communication systems).andO;Ticker:    TX.andO;Topic:     ISDNNew TechniqueIntegrated Voice/Data.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>